### Firewall Zones

Before assigning zones to networks, create them in the Unifi controller:
- [ ] Navigate to **Settings → Profiles → Zones**
- [ ] Create zone: **{{ zones.prod.name }}**
- [ ] Create zone: **{{ zones.dev.name }}**

Then assign zones to networks:
- [ ] Edit the **Prod** network → set Zone to **{{ zones.prod.name }}**
- [ ] Edit the **Dev** network → set Zone to **{{ zones.dev.name }}**

#### Inter-Zone Policies

| From | To | Policy | Reason |
|------|----|--------|--------|
| {{ zones.prod.name }} | {{ zones.management.name }} | {{ zones.prod.policy.to_management }} | Home devices reach prod services |
| {{ zones.management.name }} | {{ zones.prod.name }} | {{ zones.prod.policy.from_management }} | Prod VMs (PBS, Gatus) need NAS access |
| {{ zones.dev.name }} | {{ zones.management.name }} | {{ zones.dev.policy.to_management }} | Dev is isolated |
| {{ zones.management.name }} | {{ zones.dev.name }} | {{ zones.dev.policy.from_management }} | Nothing needs to reach dev |
| {{ zones.prod.name }} | {{ zones.dev.name }} | {{ zones.prod.policy.to_dev }} | Prod and dev are isolated |
| {{ zones.dev.name }} | {{ zones.prod.name }} | {{ zones.dev.policy.to_prod }} | Prod and dev are isolated |

Configure these policies in **Settings → Security → Zones** (or the equivalent
zone policy editor in your Unifi version). "Block" means default-deny with
exceptions added as individual firewall rules as needed.
{% else %}
### Firewall Rules

No firewall zones configured in config.yaml. Configure inter-VLAN firewall rules
manually per your gateway documentation.

**Required policies:**
- Internal → Prod: **Allow** (home devices need to reach prod services)
- Prod → Internal: **Allow selectively** (PBS and Gatus need NAS access)
- Internal → Dev: **Block** (exception: operator workstation for SSH/development)
- Dev → Internal: **Block**
- Prod ↔ Dev: **Block** in both directions
{% endif %}

### DHCP Reservations

DHCP reservations on Unifi are created via the **Clients** page, not from the
network settings.

For each VM, create a reservation:
- [ ] Navigate to **Clients** (top-level menu in the left sidebar)
- [ ] Click **+ Add Client** at the top of the page

{% for vm_name, vm in vms.items() %}
- [ ] Add client: MAC `{{ vm.mac }}`, Name `{{ vm_name }}`,
      Fixed IP `{{ vm.ip }}`.
      Leave "Local DNS Record" **unchecked**.
{% endfor %}

**Note:** "Local DNS Record" creates a record on the Unifi gateway's DNS resolver.
Leave it unchecked — DNS is managed by PowerDNS, and enabling it would create a
conflicting source of truth.

**Note:** On Unifi Network 10.x, DHCP reservations are created via the
**Clients** page (top-level sidebar), not from network settings. On earlier
versions, check Settings → Networks → [network] → DHCP Reservations.

### DHCP Guarding Check

> **WARNING:** If DHCP Guarding is enabled on your UniFi switch, VMs on tagged
> VLANs will NOT receive DHCP leases. DHCP Guarding is a security feature that
> blocks DHCP server responses on ports where they're not expected. On trunk ports
> carrying tagged VLAN traffic, this blocks the gateway's DHCP responses to VMs.

- [ ] Navigate to **Devices** → select your switch → **Ports** → select each trunk port (ports connected to Proxmox nodes)
- [ ] Check if **DHCP Guarding** is enabled (under port profile or security settings)
- [ ] If enabled: either disable DHCP Guarding on trunk ports, or add the gateway as a trusted DHCP server

To verify DHCP is working after any changes:
```bash
# Create a temporary test VM on the prod VLAN in the Proxmox UI and check
# if it receives a DHCP lease. If it gets an IP in {{ environments.prod.subnet }},
# DHCP is working. Delete the test VM afterward.
```

