### Port 53 Forwarding (DNS)

DNS queries from the internet must reach the prod DNS authoritative server.
The DNS VMs run two processes: a **recursor** on port 53 (for VLAN clients)
and the **authoritative** on port 8053 (for zone data). The port forward must
target port **8053** (the authoritative), not port 53 (the recursor).

The recursor on port 53 provides full-service DNS to internal VMs but refuses
non-recursive queries from public resolvers. The port forward must target port
8053 (the authoritative instance) which responds with the AA flag required for
valid DNS delegation.

Since a single port forward can only target one IP, forward to dns1 as primary.

**Note:** On Unifi Network 10.x, port forwarding is under **Policy Engine**
(top-level sidebar item, not inside Settings). On earlier versions, check
Settings → Routing → Port Forwarding, or Settings → Firewall & Security.

- [ ] Navigate to **Policy Engine** → **Port Forwarding** in the left sidebar
- [ ] Click **Create New Policy**
- [ ] Fill in the form:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| Name | `DNS-forward-tcp` |
| WAN Interface | All |
| Protocol | TCP |
| IP Address | (leave as default / Any — this matches your WAN IP) |
| Port | `53` |
| From | Any |
| Forward IP | `{{ vms.dns1_prod.ip }}` |
| Forward Port | `8053` |

- [ ] Click **Add** to save the rule
- [ ] Click **Create New Policy** again for UDP:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| Name | `DNS-forward-udp` |
| WAN Interface | All |
| Protocol | UDP |
| IP Address | (leave as default / Any) |
| Port | `53` |
| From | Any |
| Forward IP | `{{ vms.dns1_prod.ip }}` |
| Forward Port | `8053` |

- [ ] Click **Add** to save the rule

**Why two rules:** DNS uses both TCP and UDP on port 53. UDP handles most
queries; TCP is used for zone transfers and responses larger than 512 bytes.
Some Unifi versions have a "Both" protocol option — if available, a single rule
with Protocol "Both" is equivalent.

**Why port 8053:** The DNS VMs use a split architecture. Port 53 runs the
pdns-recursor (handles recursive queries for VLAN clients — both local zones
and external names). Port 8053 runs the PowerDNS authoritative (serves zone
data with the AA flag). Public resolvers following the NS delegation chain
require authoritative answers. The WAN port forward translates WAN:53 →
VM:8053, so public resolvers reach the authoritative directly.

**Why forwarding to dns1 only:** Unifi port forwarding sends traffic to a
single internal IP. The NS delegation at the registrar lists both dns1 and
dns2, so external resolvers will try dns2 if dns1 doesn't respond. The port
forward ensures at least one is reachable from the WAN. If true redundancy
from the WAN is needed, a more advanced setup (e.g., keepalived with a floating
VIP) can be added later.

> **Dev DNS:** No port forwarding is needed for dev DNS servers ({{ vms.dns1_dev.ip }},
> {{ vms.dns2_dev.ip }}). Dev DNS is internal-only — it serves the dev VLAN and is
> not publicly delegated. Pebble (dev ACME server) queries the DNS servers
> directly on the VLAN, not via public delegation.

### Verification

- [ ] Connect a device to the Prod VLAN:
  - [ ] Receives IP in {{ environments.prod.subnet }}
  - [ ] Gateway: {{ environments.prod.gateway }}
  - [ ] DNS: {{ vms.dns1_prod.ip }}, {{ vms.dns2_prod.ip }} (NOT {{ environments.prod.gateway }})
  - [ ] Search domain: {{ environments.prod.dns_domain }}

- [ ] Connect a device to the Dev VLAN:
  - [ ] Receives IP in {{ environments.dev.subnet }}
  - [ ] Gateway: {{ environments.dev.gateway }}
  - [ ] DNS: {{ vms.dns1_dev.ip }}, {{ vms.dns2_dev.ip }} (NOT {{ environments.dev.gateway }})
  - [ ] Search domain: {{ environments.dev.dns_domain }}

- [ ] Device on Prod VLAN cannot ping Dev gateway ({{ environments.dev.gateway }})
- [ ] Device on Dev VLAN cannot ping Prod gateway ({{ environments.prod.gateway }})

> **How to verify DNS servers on a running VM:** SSH in and run
> `networkctl status | grep DNS`. The output should show the per-environment
> DNS server IPs, not the gateway. If it shows the gateway IP, the DHCP DNS
> setting is wrong — go back to **Settings → Networks → [VLAN] → DHCP →
> DHCP Service Management → DNS Server** and set it to "Manual" with the
> correct IPs. Then restart networkd on VMs: `systemctl restart systemd-networkd`.

- [ ] From an external network (e.g., mobile phone on cellular):
  ```
  nmap -p 53 {{ public_ip }}
  ```
  Expected: port 53 shows as open (or filtered, if DNS VMs aren't running yet —
  but NOT closed/rejected, which would indicate the port forward isn't working)
